Part I: Research Question¶

A. Describe the purpose of this data analysis by doing the following:¶

1. Summarize one research question that is relevant to a real-world organizational situation captured in the selected data set and that you will answer using time series modeling techniques.

  • Using the past two years of our hospital revenue data, can we effectively forecast revenue from the hospital data by using Time Series modeling on our data?

2. Define the objectives or goals of the data analysis. Ensure your objectives or goals are reasonable within the scope of the scenario and are represented in the available data.

  • The goal of this data analysis is to be able to use Time Series Modeling, ARIMA in this case, to be able to predict future revenue from the hospital. Since we have data that showcases dates and revenue, we want our Time Series Model, ARIMA, to find any patterns and trends and incorporate that into predicting future revenues. This will be beneficial for the hospital system to be able to do further analysis as to why revenue might not be growing during certain time periods, why some time periods it is growing or if revenue is staying stagnant and not benefiting the business. Furthermore, identifying and being able to forecast from our data will can be able to help in the hospitals biggest issue seen from the WGU Data Dictionary which is readmissions.

Part II: Method Justification¶

B. Summarize the assumptions of a time series model including stationarity and autocorrelated data.¶

  • In this time series model analysis we will be using ARIMA. ARIMA stands for Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average. In order for our model to produce key results, it will rely on a few assumptions.
  • We have the assumption of stationary. Our model needs to be stationary. This indicates that our model shows our mean, variance and autocovariance in a constant matter. There are no seasonality or trends. It requires that it remains unchanged over time.
  • We then have autocorrelated data. This means that there is a relationship between timeseries and it's lagged values. In other words, this assumes that our past values in our data will influence our future values. This is crucial for making sure our model accurately reflects the patterns and trends in the data for meaningful forecasting.
  • We also have the assumption that the residuals are independent. This will note that there are no patterns or trends remaining and if they are the forecasting model won't be as efficient. To add, we also must make sure that we have no outliers in this time series data, as it will skew results and not give us those optimal results we are looking for.

C2 - Describe the time step formatting of the realization, including any gaps in measurement and the length of the sequence.¶

We did not have any gaps in measurement as seen on the graphs above. When reviewing our data we have 731 rows which is 731 days. This is 2 years and each day correlates to it's row and day. There are no gaps of days or any absent data. Since our data dictionary did not indicate a certain time series, the analysis went with year 2020. The reason for this being is because 731 rows / 2 - split into two years. It is not evenly. One will have 365 and other will have 366. 2020 was a leap year and the rest indicates 2021. From this, we decide to work in days starting January 1 as a normal calendar year. Since we do not have further information for fiscal year, it will be assumed it starts on January 1. We also note that we have 2 columns, one for date and the other for revenue. Date will be our index. Revenue is in millions. This is the type of data we will be working with. It is what time series models take, a time series object. As seen above we showcase how we converted to dates and split to two years. We see 2020-01-01 to 2021-12-31. This is the time range we will be working with.

C3 - Evaluate the stationarity of the time series¶

Below we evaluate for stationarity. We use Augmented Dickey-Fuller test for find those values and indicate whether our data is stationary or not(any trends?). We notice that it is not by noticing an upwards trend in our graphs, plus we calculate those values with tests. Recall that this is a crucial assumption in time series modeling. By ensuring we have stationarity we are building a more reliable and valid model.

C4 Explain the steps you used to prepare the data for analysis, including the training and test set split.¶

The steps used to prepare the data is first making sure we have Dates to work with for our model. We created a date column that matches the day column. The date column had the correct datetime corresponding to its days. We then dropped the day column and began working wth our new date column only. This was also used as an index. Next, we made sure we have a stationary timeseries. We must note that there should be no trend or seasonality in this data set as our model will not produce accurate results. The data was then transformed using differencing by using diff(). Differencing subrtacts the previous observation from our current observation and thus eliminating trend and seasonality. We also plot this to view how we removed any trends. Lastly, we split our data into training and test. We used train_test_split to have 80% train, 20% test for our model evaluation. We must note that since this is temporal order, we NEED to preserve that. Therefore, we use shuffle=False as to not update any order and the time series data remains as is.

The autocorrelation function¶

Below is the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation. Here, we can determine the most approrpiate order to forecast our medical revenue. We note that after before 2 lags in our ACF we have a strong correlation, but in PACF we notice our that after lag 1 we have a cut off. Thus, this leads us to have an AR model of (p), p indicating where that cut off was at, which is 1 (Brownlee 2020). This AR(1) model will go as follows (FOR NOW, until we further evaluate more numbers) - (1,1,0). p: is our lags we indicated from our plots below d: is our differencing which we used previously q: is moving average component This is relevant as our ARIMA model takes 3 different values and we must choose the best ones for our model. This also confirms when we did auto_arima and gave us the exact same numbers for our best model. We see this in our training /original set too for validation.

Part V: Data Summary and Implications¶

E. Summarize your findings and assumptions by doing the following:¶

The selection of an ARIMA model¶

The reason that an ARIMA model was selected was because the goal of our analysis was to predict future revenue values from our temporal hospital revenue data. ARIMA model has the ability to capture trends, seasonal patterns or any other underlying patterns in our revenue data. The reason why this was selected is because the ARIMA model is able to provide us with meaninful insights into our revenue over time. To add, ARIMA models are known to be robust to outliers and missing data(Pathak 2024). This means that if the hospital had revenue missing for example any insurance biling or unexpected events then our ARIMA model will ensure that it can still provide reliable forecasts despite those data discrepancies. To add we chose AR(1) model because the auto_arima indicated this was the best fit for our model. It also showed the second set of (0,0,0) as having no seasonality in our data set. When we ran ACF and PACF the graphs also indicated that this Autoregressive process with 1 lags because that one current value in our data set is based on the immediately preceding value.

The prediction interval of the forecast¶

The prediction interval of the forecast was based upon how we split our training and test sets. We decided that we would be using 80/20 split. Thus, since we used our training for our ARIMA model we will then be using our test to predict those values. The interval of 20% is 147 since we have a total of 731 observations and training used 584. With this we notice that this interval is on a forecast of 1 day. Therefore, our ARIMA model will work with any patterns or trends to predict revenue in a daily interval.

A justification of the forecast length¶

We were only given two years of data and we split our training/test into 80/20. Training set was 584 values. The rest was 147 which is a little less than half a year. A longer forecast would have required us to have even more years ahead of us to get meaningful results. This is not doable. While our data availablity is only two years (Or 731 days), it is justifiable that we use a forecast length that is not longer than our data set. Since we are working with our training/test we indicate what our length the same as our test set as seen above. To add, we are also returning back to our goal which is to effectively predict revenue and review any patterns or trends throughout our time series data. The length of 147 will give us that type of meaningful results(Dr. William Sewell 2024).

The model evaluation procedure and error metric¶

Below we evaluated the model by using Mean Absolute Error, Mean Squared Error, and Root Mean Squared Error. MAE: Model's predictions are off by about 3.560 units MSE: The squared difference between the predicted and actual values is about 2.984 units squared RMSE: On average, the model's predictions are off by about 12.6794 units Lower values indicate better perfomance which would show that the model's predictions are in par to the actual values in the data set(Awan 2023). We also recall before that we used auto_arima to call for the best model perfomance. Since our metrics are low, we can indicate that our error rates are also low.

E3. Recommend a course of action based on your results.¶

A course of action would be for the hospital to accumulate more data throughout the years. It would be more beneficial if the hospital had data ranging from when they first started to current years. Although we gathered a low RMSE, it seems attempting to forecast our model was not as beneficial as we wanted it to be. This does also play a fault into our time series forecasting. When we do forecasting, it gives us the average across the previous values and predicting it as future. It seems we did not have enough variablity and historical data for our model to do so. We did manage to find this out by looking at the predicted mean values and the mean of our data set. They both match at 16(Jain 2023). It is interesting because when we ran auto_arima, our best model was the ones we used for prediction. We also validated these numbers when we reviewed autocorrelation and partial auto correlation plots as well. This would indicate we would need further evaluation of our data set. A course of action would be to perhaps dig deeper into if there is an underlying pattern that's not showing. For example, there are other types of Time Series models and validations. These are just some of the most popular ones. Upon researching, it was indicated that time series modeling goes deeper and can retrieve results you want but this would be out of the scope of the task and not following guidelines. We have indicated a working model and reasoned why it did not achieve maximum results(Brownlee 2023).
We even prove our model is working well by reviewing it's residuals as well. We also achieve a low RMSE which indicates well compared to its average mean. It could be that the model would need to be ran a variety of times until optimal results are given rather than just attempting to showcase from auto_arima or metrics requested. This wasn't part of the scope of the project so I omitted to doing this as it would have been a bit too much and routing the scope into something completely different than what was asked for, but this would be a recommended course of action. Our forecast does not support much of our goal analysis. We have not as effectively been able to predict hospital revenue as we intended. We can further make sure our hospital administration gives us more data to work with. Also, another course of action would be for the hospital to indicate a fiscal year. This is very important for businesses as they determine how well they are doing. For example, if we were to get a larger data set with a specified fiscal year then the hospital could also run these time series quarterly. The time series model can catch any patterns and trends and indicate when they would be getting more revenue, when revenue falls or when their revenue may be getting hit with a stagnant case. It is important to note that this revenue is generalized. Hospitals do work differently and it would be beneficial if the hospital could get and pinpoint where exactly this revenue is accumulating from as well. To finalize, hospital administration can further analyze these graphs and results to indicate any sort of pattern or trends from our time series data. They can gather up information from what was going on during the hospital and further talk about why some revenue dipped or any issues they are looking for.
